{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17629654","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17629654"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:10:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:10:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17295"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17295","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17295"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0,0.05,0.24,0.68]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9985"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107512"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9985","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9985"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17295"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89992"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"7230"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23386"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23388"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23390"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39825"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107512","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107512"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department after sustaining an injury to his right forearm during a fall. He reports difficulty in moving his hand and fingers. Neurological examination reveals weakness of wrist flexion with ulnar deviation and inability to flex the fourth and fifth digits at the distal interphalangeal joints.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following nerves is most likely injured?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Axillary nerve","Musculocutaneous nerve","Radial nerve","Median nerve","Ulnar nerve"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a pattern of motor deficits consistent with injury to the \u003Cstrong\u003Eulnar nerve\u003C/strong\u003E at the forearm level. The ulnar nerve provides motor innervation to two key muscles in the forearm: flexor carpi ulnaris (which contributes to wrist flexion with ulnar deviation) and the medial half of flexor digitorum profundus (which flexes the distal interphalangeal joints of the fourth and fifth digits). Damage to the ulnar nerve at this level produces the characteristic findings described.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eaxillary nerve\u003C/strong\u003E arises from the posterior cord of the brachial plexus and innervates the deltoid and teres minor muscles. Injury results in weakness of shoulder abduction (particularly from 15-90 degrees) and external rotation, along with sensory loss over the lateral shoulder.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Emusculocutaneous nerve\u003C/strong\u003E supplies the muscles of the anterior arm compartment (coracobrachialis, biceps brachii, and brachialis). Its injury causes weakness of elbow flexion and supination, with sensory loss over the lateral forearm.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eradial nerve\u003C/strong\u003E innervates all the extensor muscles of the upper limb. High radial nerve palsy produces wrist drop, finger drop, and thumb drop due to paralysis of wrist and finger extensors. There would also be weakness of elbow extension if injured above the triceps branches.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Emedian nerve\u003C/strong\u003E innervates most flexor muscles in the forearm, including flexor carpi radialis, palmaris longus, flexor digitorum superficialis, and the lateral half of flexor digitorum profundus (to the second and third digits). However, it does not supply the muscles affected in this case. A high median nerve injury would cause loss of thumb opposition, weakness of wrist flexion with radial deviation, and inability to flex the second and third digits at the distal interphalangeal joints.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe specific combination of weakness in wrist flexion with ulnar deviation and isolated loss of distal interphalangeal joint flexion in the fourth and fifth digits localises the lesion to the ulnar nerve in the forearm, proximal to where it innervates these muscles.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The ulnar nerve innervates flexor carpi ulnaris and the medial half of flexor digitorum profundus in the forearm.","Ulnar nerve injury at the forearm level causes weakness of wrist flexion with ulnar deviation and inability to flex the fourth and fifth digits at the distal interphalangeal joints.","The flexor digitorum profundus is the only muscle that flexes the distal interphalangeal joints of the fingers."],"references":["Polcaro L, Charlick M, Daly DT. Anatomy, Head and Neck: Brachial Plexus. [Updated 2023 Aug 14]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK531473/","Sakellariou VI, Badilas NK, Mazis GA, Stavropoulos NA, Kotoulas HK, Kyriakopoulos S, Tagkalegkas I, Sofianos IP. Brachial plexus injuries in adults: evaluation and diagnostic approach. ISRN Orthop. 2014 Feb 9;2014:726103. doi: 10.1155/2014/726103. PMID: 24967130; PMCID: PMC4045362","Howard, R., Kullmann, D., Werring, D., \u0026 Zandi, M. (Eds.). (2024). Neurology: a queen square textbook. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Singh, V. (2024). Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022). The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89992"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17295"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89992","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/89992"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-30T20:35:16+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-30T20:38:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9985"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107512"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4930","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4930"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Nervous System","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-27T10:23:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"13"}},"h